Remote switched to HTTPS. GitHub no longer accepts passwords over HTTPS; use a Personal Access Token (PAT).

**Create a Personal Access Token:**
1. Go to https://github.com/settings/tokens/new
2. Name it "AIFirst Repo"
3. Select scopes: check `repo` (full control of private repositories)
4. Click "Generate token"
5. Copy the token (you won't see it again)

**Use the token:**
When you run `git push`, use:
- Username: `crestailab` (or your GitHub username)
- Password: paste the Personal Access Token

The macOS keychain will save these credentials.

Alternatively, embed the token in the URL (less secure):
```bash
git remote set-url origin https://<TOKEN>@github.com/CrestAiLab/AIFirst.git
```

Try pushing; it will prompt for credentials:
```bash
git push -u origin main
```

Remote switched to SSH. Your public key:

```
ssh-ed25519 AAAAC3NzaC1lZDI1NTE5AAAAIGEd8HcwgNkxJkbXtwTy8G6ZY3iVABDANht6ExJoptFW crestailab@gmail.com
```

Add this key to the `CrestAiLab` GitHub account:

1. Open https://github.com/settings/ssh/new (log in with `crestailab@gmail.com` or the account with access to `CrestAiLab`)
2. Paste the public key above
3. Title: "CrestAiLab Mac" or similar
4. Click "Add SSH key"

After adding it, test the connection:
```bash
ssh -T git@github.com
```

If it shows `Hi CrestAiLab! You've successfully authenticated...`, you can push:
```bash
git push -u origin main
```
